  <string name="blossom_empty_configured">No servers configured. Media can\'t be sent or received.</string>
  <string name="blossom_reset_subtitle">Re-seed the configuration with the Onym Official server.</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_relay_title">Run your own Nostr relay</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_relay_hero_body">A Nostr relay is standard open-source software that speaks the Nostr protocol — nothing Onym-specific. The steps below use strfry, a popular relay; nostr-rs-relay is another good option.</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_generic_note">Generic Nostr software — not Onym</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step1_title">Run a relay with Docker</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step1_body">strfry listens on port 7777. Data persists in a named volume.</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step2_title">Put it behind TLS</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step2_body">Clients connect over wss://, so terminate TLS with a reverse proxy on your domain (Caddy auto-issues a certificate).</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step3_title">Add it to Onym</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_step3_body">Back on Nostr Relays, paste wss://relay.example.com into \"Add Custom URL\".</string>
  <string name="run_nostr_footnote">Any spec-compliant Nostr relay works (strfry, nostr-rs-relay, and others). These are independent open-source projects, not Onym software.</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_title">Run your own Blossom server</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_hero_body">Blossom is an open spec for storing media blobs addressed by hash — nothing Onym-specific. The steps below use blossom-server (hzrd149), a common implementation.</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_generic_note">Generic Blossom software — not Onym</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step1_title">Run a server with Docker</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step1_body">blossom-server listens on port 3000. Blobs + config persist in a mounted folder.</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step2_title">Put it behind TLS</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step2_body">Onym uploads/downloads over https://, so front it with a reverse proxy on your domain (Caddy auto-issues a certificate).</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step3_title">Add it to Onym</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_step3_body">Back on Blossom Relays, paste https://blossom.example.com into \"Add Custom URL\".</string>
  <string name="run_blossom_footnote">Any Blossom-compliant server works. These are independent open-source projects, not Onym software.</string>
  <string name="deploy_hero_title">Deploy your own contract</string>
  <string name="deploy_hero_body">Build and deploy the Onym contracts from your computer with the Stellar CLI, then point Onym at the deployed address.</string>
  <string name="deploy_step1_title">Clone the contracts repo</string>
  <string name="deploy_step1_body">The Onym contracts are open source.</string>
  <string name="deploy_step2_title">Install the Stellar CLI</string>
  <string name="deploy_step2_body">Needs the Rust toolchain + the wasm32 target.</string>
  <string name="deploy_step3_title">Build the wasm</string>
  <string name="deploy_step3_body">Compiles the contracts to a wasm artifact.</string>
  <string name="deploy_step4_title">Deploy to %1$s</string>
  <string name="deploy_step4_body">Sign with your own funded account; prints a C… contract address.</string>
  <string name="deploy_step5_title">Add it to Onym</string>
  <string name="deploy_step5_body">Copy the C… address it prints, then go back and tap \"Use existing address\" to paste it in.</string>
  <string name="deploy_footnote">Deployment runs on your computer, not on the phone — the app can\'t build wasm or submit a deploy transaction directly.</string>
